Patchin Place, north from 10th (formerly Amos) Street, west of Sixth Avenue, showing the entire length of this little alley. Around 1921 the old houses were remodelled and the place painted up to attract the "Villager" type of young people who like picturesque
housing with low rents.
June, 1925.

(1)
Patchin Place, on the north side of West 10th Street, between Sixth and Greenwich Aves., showing a small dead end alley. This view shows only Nos. 1 to 9 which are on the east side of this quaint, forgotten street.

August 20, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The gate which was erected later. Photographers vantage point is on West 10th Street.

September 18, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

111-01 West 10th Street (formerly 11-1 Amos Street), north side, from Patchin Place to Sixth Avenue. These are old wooden houses which have been faced with brick. The corner lunch room was a drug store prior to 1929. There are quite a number of law offices and bail bond firms in this block of 10th Street, the Jefferson Market Magistrates' Court being on the south side at the corner of Sixth Avenue. The clearing where the camera man is standing is the site on which the new House of Detention for Women is being constructed.

The name Amos Street was dropped about the time of the Civil War, inasmuch as the eastern end of Amos Street met the western end of 10th Street at this point.

June 15, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

1938-9
Alexander Alland
